@government
go-to: menu

The United States of Brazil finds itself on its Fourth Constitution, leading many to call this period as the "Fourth Republic," or, by some critics, as the "Populist Republic." It is a presidential republic with a strong executive and a fairly strong legislative (which is divided into two chamber: the Senado and the Câmara dos Deputados.) The President takes on the role of governing, while the Congresso takes on the role of writing laws and constitutional amendments. 

The president and the vice-president are elected in different races in a direct vote plurality system, which might lead to situations were the president's party is the complete opposite to that of the vice-president. Presidents can assemble their own cabinet without any need for congressional approval, they also have the power to create as many ministries as they want. The president can be removed, legally, via resignation, impeachment or death. Congress is also elected in a plurality system.

Brazil is divided into a number of states, each of which have their own governments with some responsibilities. The most important state is São Paulo.

