= Timeline of the PTB and the Fourth Republic (until 1963)

**1945**: Getúlio Vargas is deposed under a soft coup, ending the Estado Novo. The PTB is formed in Rio de Janeiro by both Vargas and his left-wing supporters. It is was created to separate the syndicalist from the communists. It will become the fastest growing party in the nation.

**1946**: A new government under president Eurico Gaspar Dutra, of the PSD, is formed. A constitutional assembly is convened. The "liberal constitution" of 1946 will be finished by September. It reestablishes several civil liberties suspended under the Estado Novo, enshrines workers' rights and strengthens the legislative.

**1950**: Getúlio Vargas returns to power under the banner of the PTB.

**1953**: In Congress, a parliamentary inquiry commission (CPI) is established to verify claims that Getúlio Vargas used public money to support the pro-government newspaper Última Hora. The Petrobras, Brazil's state owned oil company, is founded by Getúlio Vargas after the nationalist "O petróleo é nosso!" campaign manages to garner enough nationwide support for it. 

**1954**: Several members of the military write the Manifesto dos Coronéis after Vargas increases the minimum wage by 100%. Carlos Lacerda, a journalist and major opposition figure to Vargas, is shot near his home at Rua Toneleros in the city of Rio de Janeiro. His bodyguard, Rubens Florentino Vaz, is killed. Gregório Fortunato, the head of the Presidential personal guard, confesses to the crime. The Manifesto dos Generais is written by several military leaders, it demands that Vargas resign from the presidency. One of Vargas' aide-de-camps finds a draft of a suicide note, the handwriting is from the President. He shows it to Vargas' daughter which confronts her father, he replies that it's nothing major. Vargas kills himself on August 24.

**1955**: The PSD selects Minas Gerais governor Juscelino Kubitschek as its candidate in the 1955 election. A PTB-PSD coalition is formed, naming Congressman João Goulart as Kubitschek’s running mate. The UDN selects Juarez Távora and Milton Campos as their presidential and vice-presidential nominees. Lacerda publishes the Brandi Letter, a document alleging that the Getulists intended to implement a syndicalist republic. A congressional hearing later proves the letter to be fake. Both Kubitschek and Goulart win the election.

During a funeral, General Jurandir Bizarria Mamede declares that the two winning candidates should not be inaugurated and that the military should seize power instead. This act of insubordination prompts Minister of War Henrique Teixeira Lott to ask President Café Filho—Vargas’s former vice president—to punish Mamede. His request is ignored. Café Filho then resigns due to health problems, leading the President of the Chamber of Deputies, Carlos Luz, to assume the presidency.

Luz also refuses to punish Mamede, prompting Lott to resign in protest. Soon after, Lott learns of a plot by Luz to orchestrate a coup to prevent Kubitschek and Goulart from taking office. In response, Lott launches a counter-coup. Luz is impeached, and Nereu Ramos, President of the Senate, becomes acting president.

Jânio Quadros becomes governor of São Paulo.

**1956**: Juscelino Kubitschek and João Goulart are inaugurated. Right after being sworn in, JK starts to enact his developmentalist policies by creating the Conselho de Desenvolvimento, which would soon establish the Plano de Metas, a plan to improve Brazilian infrastructure and industry. A plan to change the capital from Rio de Janeiro to a new, planned city in Goiás is approved by Congress and JK.

**1957**: A new capital, named Brasília, begins construction.

**1960**: Brasília is inaugurated. It's an election year; the candidates are Henrique Teixeira Lott of the PSD (in coalition with the PTB), Jânio Quadros of the PTN (in coalition with the UDN), and Adhemar de Barros of the PSP. Lott quickly proves himself to be an uncharismatic candidate—he wasn't a politician, after all. Quadros sweeps the election, with Goulart remaining vice president. This duo was called the "Jan-Jan" ticket (for Jânio and Jango).

**1961**: Quadros is inaugurated as president but resigns after just seven months. His resignation letter claims that "occult forces" made him leave the presidency. Goulart, who was on a diplomatic visit to Communist China, is not immediately inaugurated. This delay allows the military ministers to veto his presidency and install the President of the Câmara dos Deputados, Ranieri Mazzilli, as interim president. Leonel Brizola launches the Campanha da Legalidade, vowing to defend the constitutional line of succession. Tancredo Neves meets with Goulart in Paris to discuss a possible parliamentary system. After hours of discussion, Jango agrees. Goulart returns to Brazil, and Neves is appointed Prime Minister.

**6 January 1963**: A referendum is held to decide whether Goulart should regain full presidential powers. The result is overwhelmingly in favor. Parliamentarism is abolished.


@glossary
go-to: menu

**CPI** - Short for *Comissão Parlamentar de Inquérito*, it is an investigation committee of the legislative branch. 

**Campanha da Legalidade** - A military and civilian movement headed by Rio Grande do Sul's governor Leonel Brizola.after the military veto against João Goulart's inauguration. 

**Dispositivo Militar** - A policy by João Goulart that consisted in promoting loyal officers to important posts in both the military hierarchy and his cabinet.

**Reformas de Base** - A series of sweeping reforms to the Brazilian political, social and economic arenas promoted by the Goulart government. 


